    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk if that makes sense. can u walk me through how the circle actually works though? like if i'm moving around the circle, how do i know which key comes next? is there a specific pattern to the way it loops?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The circle of fifths is a simple, looping pattern. It's just a set of five notes, moving up a perfect fifth each time. You start on a note, and you jump up a fifth to find the next key. Think of it like a set of very organized, very slightly sharp-edged tunnels that lead from one key to the next.\n\nIf you're in Eb Major, you go up a perfect fifth from Eb to Bb. That Bb is the root of Bb Major. Then you go up a fifth from Bb to F. F is the root of F Major. Then from F to C. C is the root of C Major. And finally, from C to G. G is the root of G Major. Then from G up a fifth brings you back to D. D is the root of D Major. And from D up a fifth brings you back to A. A is the root of A Major. And from A up a fifth brings you back to E. E is the root of E Major. And from E up a fifth brings you back to B. And from B up a fifth brings you back to F#. Wait, that's not right, you loop back to the starting note",
      "source": "target",
