    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Sharp-edged tunnels\" is just a way to describe the relentless, predictable nature of the pattern, like a well-worn path that always leads to the same destination, even if the path itself is a bit jagged. The pattern repeats because of the mathematical relationship between the intervals—the perfect fifth. It's a fundamental building block of harmony, a core structure that the music uses to connect keys.\n\nThe reason it loops is because the notes in Western music are organized around these specific ratios. When you move up a perfect fifth, you are essentially moving to a note that shares a very close harmonic relationship with the starting note. It's all about those simple, pure intervals, which is what makes the music sound satisfyingly resolved, like a well-organized, perfectly stacked collection of pieces.",
